Evaluating Health of Emerging Economies Through the Eyes of Heart Valve Disease 
in the Transcatheter Era.

Arora S(1), Ramm CJ(2), Bahekar AA(3), Vavalle JP(2).

Author information:
(1)Division of Cardiology, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Chapel 
Hill, NC, USA; Division of Medicine-Cardiology, Cape Fear Valley Medical Center, 
Fayetteville, NC, USA. Electronic address: saror@email.unc.edu.
(2)Division of Cardiology, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Chapel 
Hill, NC, USA.
(3)Division of Medicine-Cardiology, Cape Fear Valley Medical Center, 
Fayetteville, NC, USA.

China and India are the 2 fastest growing major world economies. However, they 
suffer from great differences in health policies, demographics, and rates of 
population growth. Whereas China has seen a steep decline in rheumatic heart 
disease (RHD) and a rise in life expectancy, India continues to suffer from a 
significant burden of RHD due to insufficient distribution of economic 
prosperity to health care, denser population, and ineffective application of 
World Health Organization RHD prevention guidelines. As China faces the burden 
of the world's largest geriatric population, focus has shifted to calcific 
aortic stenosis for which it prepares by expansions in the field of 
transcatheter aortic valve replacement. Conversely, India has a younger 
population and a lower average life expectancy. Therefore, focus in India has 
still not shifted to calcific aortic stenosis as a major cause of morbidity and 
mortality as RHD continues to constitute the bulk of valvular heart disease.

